Analyzing Lionel Messi's Career And Predicting How Many Goals He Will Score in 2022/23¶

A Data Science Analysis¶

Jarod French
Last updated: May 14th 2022

Introduction:¶

Lionel Messi is one of the best soccer players on the planet. There has been a long debate between soccer fans whether the greatest player of all time is Messi, or if it is Cristiano Ronaldo, Pelé, the late Diego Maradona, or others. In this tutorial, we will be using python3 and all of the goals Messi has scored in his career to illustrate the Data Science Pipeline:

  1. Data collection/curation + parsing (if necessary)
  2. Data management/representation
  3. Exploratory data analysis
  4. Hypothesis testing
  5. Communication of insights attained

We will be utilising this dataset of all of Messi's club soccer goals, found on Kaggle. The dataset includes data such as the season, competition, matchday, venue, date, Messi's team, the opponent, the result, Messi's position, the minute the goal was scored, the score when Messi scored the goal, the type of goal, and who assisted the goal. The dataset was last updated April 23, 2022 so there may be a few missing goals that Messi has scored between then and now.

Python Libraries Required:¶

The first step is to import the libraries we will be using to read the data and to create plots as well as perform regression to make predictions.

  • Pandas - to format data and utilize data (API documentation)
  • Numpy - to help utilize and store data (API documentation)
  • Matplotlib.pyplot - to help visualize data and label figures (API documentation)
  • Seaborn - to build plots and graphs in order to visualize data (API documentation)

I have found a youtube video of the goal. The video shows that the data is Missing Not at Random (MNAR) because there is a reason this value was excluded from the data. The reason is that the goal is controversal, but considering the rules of the game of soccer, the goals must be a header, because goals scored with a hand don't count, although in this case the referee missed the call. You can decide if the goal is controversal or if that value should be included in a different analysis, but for the purpose of this tutorial, we'll consider it a header. The other reason is that whoever collected the data might not have been able to find a player who assisted Messi for that goal. This is less likely but either way, we have to leave the missing data alone. This does not really affect our analysis too much, however.

3. Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Now that there is no missing data, and the data is formatted in a DataFrame, lets look at Exploring and Analyzing the data. To start, let's separate the goals Messi has scored by team. Yes, I know Messi has only played for two teams and he has not even been at Paris Saint Germain for a full season, but we should start with something fairly simple to understand. We will have to calculate how many goals he scored for each team, which we will do manually to get an idea of how to calculate this.

goals_dict = {}
goals_dict['Team'] = messi['Club'].unique()

psg_count = 0

He is only behind Cristiano Ronaldo and Pelé for most scored goals ever, including national team goals.

Now lets calculate the actual average goals Messi scored over his whole career and over the 08/09 to 20/21 seasons to get a feeling for how the data is spread.

# obtain a list of each season Messi has played
seasons = messi['Season'].unique()

# make a list of DataFrames, grouped by season
seasons_list = messi.groupby('Season')

# The length of each DataFrame in seasons_list is the number of Goals Messi scored that season

for season in seasons:
    lengths.append(len(seasons_list.get_group(season).index))

# sum the total amount of goals Messi has scored and divide it by the number of total seasons
# number of total seasons is the length of the list of unique seasons in the seasons variable 
sum = 0
for season in lengths:
    sum += season
print("Messi scored approximately " + str(sum / len(lengths)) + " goals per season from 04/05 to 21/22.")

# sum the seasons from 04/05 to 20/21 in a similar way
sub_sum = 0
# 4 and 16 are the indices of lengths here that correspond to 04/05 and 20/21 respectively
for i in range(0,len(lengths)):
    if i >= 4 and i <= 16:
        sub_sum += lengths[i]
# divide by 13 because 04/05 to 20/21 is 13 seasons (inclusive)
print("Messi scored approximately " + str(sub_sum / 13) + " goals per season from 08/09 to 20/21.")

The next plot to understand the data is actually a bit fun in my opinion. We will plot the number of goals per minute section of a game Messi has scored as a histogram over the course 120 minutes so that we can include the games where Messi scored in overtime.

The first problem we will run into for this plot, is that the minute column in the DataFrame must be cleaned more because some of the goals are labeled as "90+1" or "45+2". For background, this is a byproduct of the clock never stopping in soccer, the referee will just keep track of all of the times that the game is "paused" for injury, goal celebrations, etc. and then add that time on to the end of the half. This is called stoppage time. For example, a normal half of soccer might get to the 45th minute, and then the referee adds on 2 minutes because of game stoppages, giving us the minutes 45+1 and 45+2. These are impossible to plot with integers, so they must be changed. For the purposes of this plot, we are going to consider 45+2 to be the 47th minute, and 90+1 is the 91st minute. The 47th minute is technically the first half still, but since we are not separating by halves, we can just call it the 47th minute.

In order to update these values to be integers, we are going to utilize the python regex library, re. To match the 90+1 values, we group the first set of digits, match the plus sign, and then group the second set of digits. I used rubular to help me format the regex, even though that is primarily for regex for programs in the ruby language, regex is itself its own language so I can just use single quotes in re rather than the slashes rubular uses to start and end the regex expression. We will then add the digits together so 90+1 = 91. While we do this we will ensure that all the values are ints, because far above in our info function output, the dtypes were all listed as object (most likely as a string object).

For the histogram, we'll use bins of 15 minute game time intervals, since the game is divided evenly that way.

  • re - to use regex to isolate values in strings and other expressions (API documentation)
In [50]:
import re
In [51]:
# expression to match and group the integers.
regexp = '(\d{2})\+(\d{1,2})'

# change the values to all integers as well as match the values with '+' and then add them as integers.
for i, row in messi.iterrows():
    match = re.match(regexp, row['Minute'])
    if match:
        messi['Minute'][i] = int(match.group(1)) + int(match.group(2))
    else:
        messi['Minute'][i] = int(messi['Minute'][i])

bins=[0,15,30,45,60,75,90,105,120]
# set the size of the figure
sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize' : (12,8)})
plt.xticks(bins) # Use plt.xticks to label the xticks on a seaborn plot
p = sns.histplot(data=messi,x=messi['Minute'], bins= bins) 
# label the plots
plt.ylabel("Goals")
plt.xlabel("Minute of Goal")
p.axes.set_title("Minute of Goals", fontsize=20); # semicolon so there's no extraneous output

Obviously, since overtime doesn't happen often, and never happens in league games, the 105 to 120 minute bin only represents overtime and the 10 to 105 minute bin is a combo of the first half of overtime and the goals Messi has scored in second half stoppage time. With that in mind, the low frequency of overtime occurrences leads me to believe that most of the goals in that bin are stoppage time goals. Overall, Messi seems to get better at scoring the longer a normal regulation game goes, with his goals peaking between the 75th and 90th minute. This is not to say that he isn't consistantly scoring between the 15th and 75th minute, however. This histogram is slightly skewed left since the peak is toward the right, although it is very close to symmetrical, meaning Messi is pretty much a dangerous goalscorer no matter what minute of the match it is.

Goals can also be scored in a variety of ways, but Messi scores a large variety of goals. While players tend to score with left or right footed shots or headers, Messi scores with many more types of goal. This is important to see that Messi is not just what some people call a "one trick pony".

Let's revisit the goals per competition. It is pretty obvious how many goals Messi has scored for Barcelona since La Liga, Copa del Rey and most of Messi's UEFA Champions League goals were scored while he was at Barcelona. Let's analyze Messi's goals per game ratios in three different competitions: La Liga, Ligue 1, and the UEFA Champions League. Standardizing the goals per game will show us how prolific Messi is in each competition. To do that, we will write a function that cuts the dataset into several datasets.

In [53]:
# dataset = data to use, group_names are the names of the chunks,
# column_name is the name of the column to sort by to get the chunks
def cut_dataframe_into_chunks(dataset, group_names, column_name):
    # with the data cut into the number of bins, append each bin into a list of datasets based on the groups above
    tables = []
    for curr in group_names:
        tables.append(dataset.groupby(column_name).get_group(curr))
    return tables

group_names = messi['Competition'].unique()
grouped_messi = cut_dataframe_into_chunks(dataset=messi, group_names=group_names, column_name='Competition')

Now we have a list of DataFrames, one for the goals Messi has scored in each competition. We are in need of the total amount of games Messi has played in each competition in order to do this. Since our dataset only has the games in which Messi scores, it does not include games in which he does not score, so we will be relying on another dataset. Another thing we need to clean is that in the Comp column, because some of the competitions include "1." in front of them, so to make it easier to read, we are going to replace the "1." with an empty string, effectively getting rid of it. We will also rename some of the competitions to match the competitions in our other DataFrame.

Messi has scored almost 1 goal per game in la liga, which is incredible to average almost a goal per game over 519 games. Most players would be lucky to average a goal a game for a 3 game stretch, but Messi did it for more then 500 games. The Champions League average is also impressive as Messi has scored 0.8 goals per game. The UEFA Champions League is a competition where all of the best teams in Europe, which are also the best teams in the world play against each other. So Messi averages 0.8 goals per game against the best teams in the world. This is a very impressive feat. However, on the other hand, he only averages 0.166666 goals per game in Ligue 1 in France for Paris Saint-Germain. This is definitely disappointing, even though Messi has only played 24 games in Ligue 1. As an aside (that is biased on personal opinion), Messi leaving Barcelona for Paris after 17 years, one would expect there would be a year to get used to a new league, and I would hope he does better in the 2022/23 season.

There is also the fact that Messi has played for Barcelona and Paris Saint-Germain(PSG) in the champions League, so we will take a look at how he has performed in the Champions League with Barcelona and PSG separately and compare them.

In [57]:
# get dataframes of the goals Messi scored in the champions league on each team.
barca_ucl_goals = grouped_messi[1][grouped_messi[1]['Club'] == "FC Barcelona"]
psg_ucl_goals = grouped_messi[1][grouped_messi[1]['Club'] == "Paris Saint-Germain"]
# count the values in the date column to get the total number of goals he scored.
# you can use any column, since each row corresponds to a goal, date is just an arbitrary selection
barca_goals = barca_ucl_goals['Date'].count()
psg_goals = psg_ucl_goals['Date'].count()

# obtain the number of games Messi played in the champions league on each team.
ucl_games_df = playing_time[playing_time['Comp'] == "UEFA Champions League"]
barca_ucl_games = ucl_games_df[ucl_games_df['Squad'] == "Barcelona"]['MP'].sum()
psg_ucl_games = ucl_games_df[ucl_games_df['Squad'] == "Paris S-G"]['MP'].sum()

# calculate Messi's goals per game on each team. 
barca_ucl_gpg = barca_goals / barca_ucl_games
psg_ucl_gpg = psg_goals / psg_ucl_games

print("Messi has scored " + str(barca_ucl_gpg) + " goals per game in the UEFA Champions League for FC Barcelona.")
print("Messi has scored " + str(psg_ucl_gpg) + " goals per game in the UEFA Champions League for Paris Saint-Germain.")

Messi has scored 0.8053691275167785 goals per game in the UEFA Champions League for FC Barcelona.
Messi has scored 0.7142857142857143 goals per game in the UEFA Champions League for Paris Saint-Germain.

We can see that Messi has actually kept up his ridiculously good average goals per game in the Champions League while he is on PSG. This is very impressive especially considering his disappointing Ligue 1 tally.

4. Hypothesis Testing¶

Now we want to predict how many goals messi will score in the future. We must revisit Messi's goals per season statistics. He is already 34, but he should have at least one more year, but hopefully a few more years of playing soccer left in his career. Here we are looking at the impact the season and therefore Messi's age has on his goal total for the season.

Our Null Hypothesis is that the Season does not affect the goal total.

To do this regression, we will need to import the statsmodels and SciKit Learn libraries.

  • Statsmodels api - gives us a least squares regression (API documentation)

  • Scikit Learn - To do polynomial regression analysis (API documentation)

    • Sklearn.linear_model is for performing regression analysis and plotting it.
    • Sklearn.preprocessing we will use for getting polynomial features since we are actually doing polynomial regression since the curve we will fit will be a 2nd order polynimial
In [58]:
from statsmodels import api as sm
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures;

We do the statsmodels regression first, using least squares.

In [59]:
# calculate goals per season list
# Change seasons to just the beginning year, to form a sort of timeline.
for i in range(0, len(seasons)):
    seasons[i] = seasons[i].split('/')
    seasons[i] = '20' + seasons[i][0]

# first get a DataFrame with just the goals and seasons.
goals_per_year_df = pd.DataFrame()
goals_per_year_df['Season'] = seasons
goals_per_year_df['Goals'] = lengths
goals_per_year_df['Season'] = goals_per_year_df.Season.astype(int)

# our x and y values for the regression
x = goals_per_year_df['Season']
y = goals_per_year_df['Goals']

We will use the season as our x and the number of goals as our y to do the regression. With statsmodels, you must add the constant (x) manually.

# add constant
sm_x = sm.add_constant(x)

Looking at the coefficient of season, it seems to have little impact on the number of goals since it is so close to 0 (1.873e-06). Although since the P value of the season variable is 0.000, which is less than the critical value of 5% (p value of 0.05), the season has significance within the model.

Therefore, we can reject the null Hypothesis that the season does not have any affect on how many goals Messi scores.

Our model has a R-squared value of 0.787 which is pretty close to fitting, and it also doesn't overfit the data, so we are good to plot the model, using sklearn.

OLS fit our data for us, but if you take a look back at our goals per season graph, we can see the data is parabolic which is a 2nd order polynomial and not linear so we must use polynomial fitting.

In [61]:
# we must first reshape the season array because sklearn likes it a certain way.
X = goals_per_year_df['Season'].to_numpy().reshape(-1,1)

# # do the regression
# lin = LinearRegression()
# lin.fit(X,y)

poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree=2)
X_poly = poly.fit_transform(X)

poly.fit(X_poly, y)
lin2 = LinearRegression()
lin2.fit(X_poly,y)
plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))
plt.scatter(x,y, color='blue')
plt.plot(X, lin2.predict(poly.fit_transform(X)), color='red')
plt.ylim(ymin=0)
plt.ylabel("Goals")
plt.xlabel("Season")
plt.title("Messi's Goals per Season with a Polynomial Regression Curve", fontsize=20)
plt.xticks(ticks=goals_per_year_df['Season']);

In accordance with our R-squared value, the model does not overfit the data, rather it follows the trend as it was designed to do. With this however we can plug in future years in order to predict Messi's future season goal totals. Let's predict how many goals Messi will score in 2022/23. Sklearn uses an array transform to do this so we will plug in the 2022 value as an array.

In [62]:
pred = 2022
predarr = [[pred]]
lin2.predict(poly.fit_transform(predarr))

array([5.26960783])

The array that was printed contians the goal total the model predicted Messi will score in the 2022/23 season. This is quite a measly total, but the data says that that's all he will score if he plays the same as he has been for the past few years, this past year especially. If we follow the curve, we can see where the value of roughly 5.27 goals comes from.

5. Conclusions and Insights Attained¶

Throughout this analysis, we have seen Messi's goals in a number of different ways and ended up predicting his goal total for the 2022/2023 season in all competitions. Messi has scored a total of 681 goals across several competitions at the club soccer level, averaging 37.8 goals per year over his entire career. He has scored in a variety of ways, with his left foot being incredibly accurate and lethal, as well as scoring over a large range of minutes in a match, while playing five different positions in his career. Messi also averaged almost a goal per game in La Liga and the UEFA Champions League in his time at FC Barcelona as well as averaging 0.7 goals per game in the Champions League in his short time at PSG.

From all of these stats, we can conclude that Messi is one of the greatest players of all time, if not the single greatest player. While this is a very opinionated and biased topic, the data proves Messi's accomplishments are absolutely earned. Even though we predicted he will score only 5 goals next season in 2022/2023, soccer fans around the world hope for a resurgence from Messi to return to his Barcelona form and score 40 goals per season again.
